The paper deals with the problem of coalitional manipulation in elections, which is a topic in computational social choice (cs.GT). The paper also proposes new algorithms based on intuitions from bin-packing and multiprocessor scheduling, which are topics in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The empirical evaluation of the algorithms involves testing them on randomly generated elections, which is a topic in machine learning (cs.LG) and multi-agent systems (cs.MA).
